TDD exercise complete. All 9 tests pass across the full Game of Life implementation:

**Tests implemented (9/9):**
1. Empty grid → empty grid
2. Single cell dies (underpopulation)
3. Two adjacent cells die (underpopulation)
4. Block (2x2) stays unchanged (still life)
5. Cell with 2 neighbors survives
6. Cell with 3 neighbors survives
7. Cell with >3 neighbors dies (overpopulation)
8. Dead cell with 3 neighbors becomes alive (reproduction)
9. Blinker oscillates vertical → horizontal

**Implementation** (`src/game-of-life.ts`): Sparse representation using a `Set<string>` of coordinate keys. The `nextGeneration` function filters survivors (live cells with 2-3 neighbors) and finds newborns (dead cells adjacent to live cells with exactly 3 neighbors). Helper functions `toKey`, `parseKey`, `neighborKeys`, and `countNeighbors` keep the code clean.
